### **1. Sell Timing — Was it Right?**
- **Verdict:** **Mixed/Too early for the full move, but disciplined for the strategy.**
- **Details:** Eva sold on March 12th at $1.86, capturing a 16% gain in a single day. The exit was triggered by technical exhaustion signals (RSI 71.4, Bollinger %B 105.1).
- **Counterfactual:** If held to today (March 20th), the option would be worth $2.40 (+50%). The peak was today (March 20) at $3.35 (+109%).
- **Why she sold:** She followed the "RSI >70 + Bollinger %B >100" profit-taking rule. This rule is designed to lock in gains at statistical extremes. In this case, while the stock pulled back briefly, it eventually overcame the extreme signals due to persistent geopolitical news (Iran conflict/Oil >$100).

### **2. Could Eva have sold at a better price?**
- **Verdict:** **Yes, significantly, by ignoring/nuancing the technical exhaustion signal during structural news catalysts.**
- **Details:** The option hit $3.35 today (March 20).
- **Missed Opportunity:** Exiting on the technical signal at $1.86 missed out on an additional $1.49 per contract (+93%).

### **3. Could Eva have rebought after selling?**
